<seg id=1> Lien Hoe Is Expected to Redeem the Rest 65% of the Bonds </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Kuala Lumpur) Lien Hoe is expected to redeem the rest 65% of the bonds, whose tatal value is 53,810,000 lingji, at the end of this year by getting the loan finacing from banks. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> 6% of the annual rate of Lien Hoe could redeem the assured bonds, its issued total value is 85,740,000 lingji, and its expiration date is August 17, 1998. </seg>
<seg id=4> Due to the drop of the real estate market and the inflation of speculative capital, when Lien Hoe comes to its expiration date, only 35% of the bonds can be redeemed, at the same time, the expiration date of the rest 65% may be postponed to August 17, 2000 at an annual rate of 15%. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> It was in last month that the Stock Exchange Supervision Committee approved of Lien Hoe's postponing the expiration date of its bonds to August 17, 2000. Meanwhile, this group was the first company that was allowed to postpone the expiration date of its bonds. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Due to the drop of the present market interest rate, Lien Hoe planned to redeem the rest bonds by bank loans, without paying the bondholders at a higher annual rate of 15%. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Zeng Hualong, chairman and manager of the board of directors of this company declared that since the present interest rate has dropped, and the new financial budget plan was favorable to the development of real estate, Lien Hoe was expected to turn the table in the second half of the year, and achieve satisfactory performance in the second half of the year. </seg>
</p>
